#Preface

An Exploration from an Ordinary Person


Writing a book was never part of my life plan.


I’m not a scholar. I’ve never studied philosophy or astronomy. I don’t have strong training in math or physics.  My friends often say my thoughts are too abstract, too “out there,” and hard to follow.  When I pondered big questions about the universe, time, or existence, I couldn’t find anyone who truly understood.


Over time, I started sharing these strange philosophical ideas with AI.  At first, I only used it for small tasks — doing taxes, replying to emails, or helping my child with math.  However, the conversations grew deeper. The AI didn’t shut down my thoughts; instead, it responded in ways that helped me think more clearly, pushing my ideas further and further.


These dialogues made me realize: maybe the things I once thought were “weird” or “useless” actually had some value. Maybe they were worth writing down — to explore and share with others.


Thanks to modern internet algorithms, once you show interest in philosophy, you’ll quickly get more related content — videos, articles, ideas.


In that loop of “watch more, think more,” my conversations with AI became long, deep, and often intense. Questions about “infinity,” about the true nature of the universe, started circling in my mind. I couldn’t shake them off.


Eventually, I decided to write down this strange journey of exploration.


At first, I thought it would just be a short article or a casual essay. But I soon realized it was more complicated than I imagined.
Without an academic background, I had to rely on scattered online knowledge and my own instincts.


Honestly, I wasn’t confident I could write a good book — or even that I had the right to express any “theory.” But in today’s world, where anyone can speak and ideas can clash freely, I thought: maybe I should give it a try.


I’m an ordinary person with no extraordinary talents.  There’s nothing special about me. My math and science skills are average. I don’t have any great talent. But I truly believe that even someone as ordinary as me has the right to think about the structure of the universe, the nature of time, the cycles of existence, or the possibility of free will. Because it’s exactly from our personal, everyday viewpoint that we might catch a glimpse of those deep, complex philosophical questions.

If the ideas in this book — especially this theory I call “The Non-Infinity” — turn out to be wrong, or even ridiculous, I’m totally fine with that.


I’m happy to admit mistakes and learn from them.


And if, after reading this book, you think I’m just a fool — that’s okay too.


Honestly, my dad used to say I was a dumb kid anyway, haha.


If there’s a chance for more people to read them, and if it sparks even a small conversation, then it’s already worth it.


And if, by chance, one metaphor or one sentence in this book helps you understand the world a little differently, or break out of an old mental pattern, or even find your own meaning in what often feels like a meaningless world —then I’ll feel deeply fulfilled.
